description:
Persons in need of international protection can enter the country without penalization, or fear of refoulement, and in full
respect for their rights, and have access to appropriate entry procedures and reception conditions; Asylum-seekers have their
claims processed in a timely, fair and efficient manner with due procedural safeguards, including access to legal remedies;
Children of concern are included in national child protection systems and have access to child friendly procedures and services;
Refugees have access to socio-economic rights and livelihoods

National and local policies and programmes facilitate socio-economic integration of forcibly displaced and stateless people.;
Voluntary internal relocation is available to a higher and more diverse number of forcibly displaced and stateless people in
coordination with authorities and civil society organizations.

Refugees and asylum seekers benefit from efficient and functional referral mechanisms; Access to civil registration and identity
documentation is improved for stateless persons and all children born in the country are registered with a civil authority.;
Asylum seekers have access to fair and efficient RSD procedures

Support to the Government to actualize the refugee-related pledges and include refugee in national systems is provided;
Support to meet humanitarian and development needs of refugees and their hosts is provided; Human capital development,
sustainable livelihoods and economic inclusion of refugees and their hosts are promoted

By 2026, all asylum seekers have acces to territory.; By 2026, harmonized and efficient registration systems is in place for new
arrival.; BY 2026, all Forcibly Displaced and Stateless persons have access to fair and efficient status determination procedure.;
By 2026, all forcibly displaced persons receive multisectoral assistance and have access to basic services

Strengthening community involvement and participation in the empowerment and peaceful cohabitation of communities.;
Forcibly displaced and stateless persons have access to housing systems, emergency shelter, temporary and permanent
housing.

All persons of concern are registered in the asylum system, are protected from refoulement and receive adequate support by
the authorities, including prompt identification, response and rehabilitation for SGBV survivors and children of concern.;
Persons of concern have access to quality and timely status determination procedures; Persons are empowered by self-sufficient through employment, language and vocational training, have stable residence and communal-support mechanisims

Access to territory is guaranteed to Forcibly displaced and stateless personsn to UNHCR in need of international protection;
Protection of at-risk groups including children and people with disabilities is achieved; Community-based protection
mechanisms are strengthened

Persons in need of international protection can enter the country without penalization, or fear of refoulement, and in full
respect for their rights, and have access to appropriate entry procedures and reception conditions; Asylum-seekers have their
claims processed in a timely, fair and efficient manner with due procedural safeguards, including access to legal remedies;
Children of concern are included in national child protection systems and have access to child friendly procedures and services;
Persons of concern are positively perceived and supported by host communities; State actors implement social cohesion
policies and actions with participation by civil society and refugee communities

Improved access to adequate preventive, promotive and curative services for communicable and non communicable diseases.;
Inclusive, equitable and quality education at all levels for all refugee and host communities; Satisfactory and dignified
conditions of sanitation and hygiene for refugee and host communities; Water services are integrated in national structures;
Coordination with Office of the Prime Minister (OPM), District Local Government and Partners strengthened

Improved access to adequate preventive, promotive and curative services for communicable and non communicable diseases.;
Improved Sexual Reproductive Health services, HIV/Tuberculosis (TB) prevention, care, treatment services; Reduced Global
Acute Malnutrition, Anaemia & Stunting

People of concern have access to efficient registration and documentation processes, and access to territory is preserved;
Legislation and administrative practices related to aspects impacting on refugees’ rights and access to services are more
inclusive and aligned with international standards

GBV survivors have access to a holistic response and prevention plan by 2024; Children of concern under our mandate are
protected from violence, abuse, exploitation and discrimination and have access to child friendly procedures and services;
Forcibly displaced people have access to basic needs to ensure their well-being and dignity by 2024

2.5. By 2025, food security status of forcibly displaced people is improved.; 2.7. By 2025, forcibly displace people can access
habitable and affordable housing.; 4.5. By 2025, implementation of the Global Compact on Refugees framework is improved;
2.9. By 2025, UNHCR supply chain and operational support is timely and effective

Refugees, asylum-seekers, IDPs and IDP returnees have improved access to services and assistance to meet their basic needs.;
Refugees, asylum-seekers, IDPs and IDP returnees have improved access to sustainable sites, shelters, energy and environment
management.

Refugees, asylum-seekers, IDPs and IDP returnees have improved access to services and assistance to meet their basic needs.;
Refugees, asylum-seekers, IDPs and IDP returnees have improved access to sustainable sites, shelters, energy and environment
management.

Refugees live in safety from gender-based violence (GBV), and those at risk and survivors have access to specialized services.;
Refugee children are protected and those at risk have access to specialized and child-friendly services.; Refugees with specific
needs have access to specialized protection services without obstacles.

People of concern have access to efficient registration and documentation processes, and access to territory is preserved;
Legislation and administrative practices related to aspects impacting on refugees’ rights and access to services are more
inclusive and aligned with international standards

Strengthening community involvement and participation in the empowerment and peaceful cohabitation of communities.;
Forcibly displaced and stateless persons have access to cooking energy in a sustainable and environmentally-friendly manner;
By 2024, improvement of productive assets

Refugees, asylum seekers, have access to sustainable housing and settlement with adequate environment and energy; Refugee
children and youth have access to ECD, primary, secondary and tertiary education with vocational and recreation support;
Refugees and asylum seekers have improved access to systems and facilities providing water, sanitation and hygiene services.;
Refugees and host communities access economic opportunities; Refugees enjoy safe and dignified return to their Country of
Origin
